tell you the truth, I can't quite recall when that 
was. Oh yes, I moved to Bryan. I moved to Bryan after

22:02.389 --> 22:09.598
I got married, which was about 1926. Then in 26, I 
lived in that location until I

22:10.085 --> 22:26.464
was made head of department. That's when I moved to 
campus. And

22:29.788 --> 22:37.797
I simply can't recall when I moved off the campus. 
Oh yes, I did. I moved to another house on the

22:42.549 --> 22:53.383
campus, which was down by the old swimming pool, 
and lived in that house for several years. And then

22:54.324 --> 23:07.902
about 19...

22:54.324 --> 23:07.902
Can't seem to get my dates very clear in there. 
moved off the campus and lived off the campus a year

23:08.557 --> 23:16.767
before I built a house up on the hill in front of 
College Station. That big two-story house up on

23:17.147 --> 23:21.953
the hill there was my home where I built it. In which 
area though? It's right out in front of the campus,

23:23.996 --> 23:29.943
about half a mile off the campus, up on the hill. 
It's on, is it at Eastgate? Across Highway 6. Oh,

23:32.125 --> 23:33.066
it's at Eastgate. Yeah, Eastgate. And I built that 
house in 19...

23:41.227 --> 23:46.172
I believe it was 40, a year after I moved off campus. 
Was that in College Hills Estate that you built

23:46.673 --> 23:49.475
your house? Well, it was part of College Hills 
Estate, yes. I believe that's what they called it.

23:56.242 --> 24:01.768
Okay, do you remember the public school system 
that was on campus for a while? Do you remember that

24:01.788 --> 24:02.789
at all? Yes, I remember the building. It was a 
stucco, two-story stucco building over in the

24:04.250 --> 24:10.677
area where the core area now is. It's really not 
quite, it's almost where the road, the street

24:13.561 --> 24:34.890
coming down by the MSC now makes that bend right at 
the area that houses the core. And that's where the

24:34.910 --> 24:35.471
school? Yes, that's where the school building 
was. Did any professors at A&M volunteer their

24:39.158 --> 24:43.282
time and teach there? I think maybe that there was a 
little bit of that, but Mr. George Wilcox was

24:43.863 --> 24:52.111
superintendent of that school and was a good one 
too. And they had a real good school for the time and

24:52.691 --> 25:01.280
they had full-time teachers. I don't remember. I 
remember the names of one or two, but Mr. Wilcox I

25:06.648 --> 25:11.794
remember very distinctly because he's such a fine 
person. Is he dead now? Yes, he's been dead a good

25:12.775 --> 25:14.598
many years. When your children went to school, did 
they go to the one that was on Jersey Street or did

25:15.799 --> 25:22.447
they go on campus? I had one daughter and

25:22.467 --> 25:34.562
she was born while we were living on the campus and

25:37.715 --> 26:06.777
While we were living on the campus, she grew up to 
enter school, but by that time they had organized

25:37.715 --> 26:06.777
President

25:37.715 --> 26:06.777
College Station School, Independent School 
District, and she went to that school for one or two

25:37.715 --> 26:06.777
years, and then she went to Bryan for several 
years, and finally, while we were living up on the

26:07.617 --> 26:15.910
hill, why she went to Bryan and graduated from 
Bryan High School. Is there any reason why she went

26:15.930 --> 26:20.177
to Bryan rather than the College Station School? I 
don't really remember any. We felt like that Bryan

26:23.202 --> 26:30.213
was an older school system and better 
established. I guess I had gone there. That might

26:32.277 --> 26:34.941
have influenced me some.

26:38.144 --> 26:46.975
Can you remember what, before it became a city in 
the 30s and the 40s, can you remember what College

26:38.144 --> 26:46.975
Station looked like physically? Any commercial 
developments?

26:51.842 --> 26:54.345
There were very little commercial developments. 
There was one or two stores at the north gate and

26:54.365 --> 27:07.442
there wasn't anything on the east gate and there 
was little development. that was built across

27:08.384 --> 27:38.273
from the campus on the southwest corner of the 
campus, south corner, you might say, of the

27:08.384 --> 27:38.273
campus, there were about 10 or 12 of those project 
houses, which were two-story wooden frame

27:08.384 --> 27:38.273
buildings in which the men were allowed to live and 
they brought most of their food from the farms And

27:38.607 --> 27:44.956
they had those, some of them had cows, brought cows 
and chickens. And Dan Russell was the man who was

27:45.457 --> 27:51.625
the head of the project houses. He was a graduate of 
Baylor University and was down here for many years

27:52.387 --> 28:00.518
as head of rural sociology department. And there 
was a small community area built up right along in

28:05.641 --> 28:18.039
there in the early 30s, which was just south of the 
campus, which was along where there was one or two

28:05.641 --> 28:18.039
stores, one or two filling stations. This 
happened because of the project housing? Well,

28:20.924 --> 28:24.349
this was just off the campus. The project houses 
were on the campus. Oh, I see. Okay. The American

28:27.874 --> 28:35.445
Legion built a little housing, well, built a 
two-story building in there I believe it was two

28:35.746 --> 28:37.668
story, I'm not sure of that. But anyway, the 
American Legion sponsored that and built that

28:38.409 --> 28:52.746
house to help the students who were members of the,

28:38.409 --> 28:52.746
what? American Legion? No, it wasn't the American 
Legion. It was, I can't think of the name of it,

28:58.653 --> 29:05.601
connected with Masonic Lodge. Not the Masons? 
Yeah. I don't remember the name of the

29:09.876 --> 29:18.089
organization, but they built the houses because 
housing was so badly needed. These were for

29:18.750 --> 29:20.993
students, right? Yes, they were for students. And 
you said to, that's on the southwest corner of

29:22.856 --> 29:26.542
campus? Yes. And then you said off of campus in the 
south, a rural community? That was across the

29:30.889 --> 29:32.432
present highway. Oh. Well, the Welburn Road runs 
parallel to the railroad. This is at right angles,

29:39.901 --> 29:45.648
crosses just beyond the campus, now goes out to the 
airport. Okay. That's the main road that goes from

29:48.152 --> 29:58.125
the President, Texas Avenue, right across the 
edge of the campus and goes on out to the airport. It

29:58.746 --> 30:03.432
was just across the road there that had this little 
commercial development. Okay. I would like to

30:08.868 --> 30:13.234
talk about the incorporation of College Station, 
if you remember that. Do you remember when it was

30:15.557 --> 30:32.322
incorporated in 39 and... Well, a real good friend 
of mine, professor of mathematics, Dr. John

30:15.557 --> 30:32.322
Binney, was, I believe, the first mayor of College 
Station and he was mayor for several years until

30:33.415 --> 30:46.593
Professor Ernest Langford became mayor and after 
he became mayor he was mayor for about 20 years.

30:47.814 --> 30:48.215
That's right. And he taught me when I was a freshman 
at A&M. Mr. Langford did? Mr. Langford did. He was a

30:55.625 --> 30:57.347
very good friend of mine. Well, do you remember any 
of the reasons why the communities around A&M

30:57.817 --> 31:05.589
campus wanted to incorporate into a town? At that 
time, the Bryan City Council decided that it was

